Introduction

The purpose of this project is to estimate home prices in Mecklenburg County, NC for Zillow. Having a reliable estimate of property values can help individuals budget and understand the costs associated with properties that meet their living standards. Having these estimates enables individuals to get the correct financing for their home. Additionally, it ensures that the buyer and the seller are getting fair value for their asset. Considering the housing bubble that caused an economic recession it is important that prices are reflected as accurately as possible to avoid negligent buying attitudes. To evaluate the home prices in Mecklenburg County we will utilize an OLS regression model which essentially describes the relationship between one or more independent quantifiable variables and dependent variables. In our case our independent variable is price and the dependent variables are internal characteristics (bedrooms, fireplace, etc) and amenities/public services. In other words, we are looking at the indicators that affect home values in Mecklenburg County. The difficulty of this exercise is standardizing house values because what people value in homes is subjective and differs from person-to-person.

inputdf.geom <- homesales %>% filter(toPredict != 'CHALLENGE') %>%

Data

The Data we are using is from the Mecklenburg open data portal. The primary dataset contains information related to the last sale price of homes in Mecklenburg County. We will use the home sale price as our independent variable. The data set also contains internal characteristics of the homes. We had to consider which of the 83 variables in the data set were considered useful influences on the price.

For the numeric variables we use in our regression we considered these four variables:

  • number of bedrooms (bedrooms)
  • number of fireplaces (numfirepla)
  • heated area (heatedarea)
  • full bathrooms (full baths = bathrooms with washing apparatus, toilet and sink).

Lastly, we utilized park amenities data which was retrieved from Mecklenburg’s open data portal. By measuring the average distance to the three nearest playgrounds from a home we were able to create variable parks_nn3. This concluded the numeric variables in our table. Additionally, we collected the school district boundaries data to see if the school catchment areas impacted house value. This formed part of our categorical variables. Our categorial variables included inputs such as:

  • Exterior Walls (extwalls = what material of the wall is made of)
  • has AC (actype)
  • Condition of the building (bldggrade)
  • High School (HIGH_NAME)

We have omitted the summary table of the categorical variables in this portion of the report, but later in this report we will show the beta coefficients of each variable used in our regression model.

Methods

The modelling technique used for this analysis is linear regression. Our target variable is home sale price which we logarithmically transformed to make more normally distributed. We removed outlier observations where home values were greater than $10,000,000.00 and the number of bedrooms were greater than 40. To select our predictor variables we looked through the provided data set and considering the predictive power of each, we determined which variables to include. We did this by using our intuition (trial and error) and limited understanding of home evaluation. Furthermore using Mecklenburg’s open data portal we included variables of school districts and average distance to three nearest playgrounds.

We created a 60/40 training-test split to analyze our models predictive power. We did this by calculating the effect each independent variable has on the target variable (training set). And then we took this model and we ran it on the test set. By analyzing the difference between our predictive values and actual values of sale price we can judge the model. We put 60% of the data in the training set and 40% in the test set.

Finally we ran a cross validation test on the model. Creating 100 folds in which we tested the model on a hold out group. A hold out group is one one hundredth of the data that is the test set for that fold.

Results

Our model has a Mean Absolute Percent Error of 0.0164, meaning on average, our model erred by 1.64% when predicting home prices. Furthermore the R-squared is 0.69 which means the model accounts for 69% of the variation in the home sale price.

inputdf.test <-
  inputdf.test %>%
  mutate(SalePrice.Predict = predict(model_train, inputdf.test),
         SalePrice.Error = SalePrice.Predict - lnprice,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(SalePrice.Predict - lnprice),
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(SalePrice.Predict - lnprice)) / SalePrice.Predict)

Impact of predictor variables on price

Below is the list of the predictor variables that we included in the model with their beta coefficients. The beta coefficient refers to the percent change in the target variable when the predictor variable changes by 1 unit. Furthermore the p-value refers to whether the value of the coefficient is statistically different from zero. A p-value less than 0.05 will indicate that this is the case.

Can our model be generalized to new data?

As we were running cross-validation tests with 100 folds we calculated 100 regressions and this shows the MAE of each. The mean is around 0.21 this shows that our model is generalizable to new data.

inputdf.cv <- trainControl(method = 'cv', number = 100)


model.cv <- 
  train(lnprice ~ ., data = inputdf %>% select(-price, -musaID), 
        method = "lm", trControl = inputdf.cv, na.action = na.pass)



ggplot(model.cv$resample)+
  geom_histogram(aes(x = MAE))+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(x = 'Mean Absolute Error', y='', title = 'CV MAE Histogram',
       subtitle = paste('# Folds = 100, mean = ',round(mean(model.cv$resample$MAE),4), ', sd = ', round(sd(model.cv$resample$MAE),4), sep = ''))

Spatial lag and Moran’s I

Since there is a positive relationship between the price error and the spatial lag of the price error that means there is spatial auto-correlation for the error. This is also seen in the Moran’s I histogram below where the observed Moran’s I is way out of range of what would normally be seen if error was randomized.

coords <- st_coordinates(inputdf.test.sf) 

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords, 5))

spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")


inputdf.test.sf <- inputdf.test.sf %>%
  mutate(lagPriceError = lag.listw(spatialWeights, SalePrice.Error),#error lag
         laglnPrice = lag.listw(spatialWeights, lnprice))

k1 <- ggplot(inputdf.test.sf, aes(exp(laglnPrice), exp(lnprice)))+
  geom_point(alpha = .5)+
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color = 'green')+

Conclusion

Our model is effective to some degree, but with more time to dedicate to feature engineering the accuracy could be increased. It is interesting to see the impact that the school district has on the price of a home. Other notable predictors like the exterior wall and building grade were important to the model as well. Although our model falls short on the accuracy of the individual price prediction of homes, it is effective in painting the broad picture of the housing market in Mecklenburg County. We can clearly and accurately distinguish the wealthiest areas from the lower priced areas.

In the race context analysis, the MAPE’s between groups was fairly similar (20% to 23%). Regardless of the racial makeup or other grouping characteristics of an area a customer is searching in, the model should provide similar accuracy in predictions.

Typically individual(s) seeking to buy a home know what income bracket they fall under. Specificity of individual house price is somewhat irrelevant in the sense that it doesn’t keep in to account which home is actually on the market. Therefore the value of a home isn’t really known until it is on the market and there are many unpredictable factors like the speed someone wants to sell there home for, or whether it is a recession or housing bubble, and/or how long a home has been on the market. In a nutshell each home sale price is circumstantial.

Recommendation

Our model is very useful and effective at providing a broad overview of the housing market in Mecklenburg County. As mentioned in our discussion our model can confidently give a potential buyer an accurate overview of where prices of homes are high or low. However our model falls short in it’s specificity, it cannot accurately predict the actual home value because of lack of data on previous home sale history and sub-optimal feature engineering. For this reason we wouldn’t recommend our model to Zillow because Zillow’s platform enables homebuyers to have accurate knowledge on property value on which they can act upon directly. Our model could only inform a potential buyer on which neighborhoods are desirable or highly valued. They would still need to undergo another process to find the correct estimates.
